The primary objective of this study was to develop a fluorescence-based sensor for the detection of LST using core–shell AgNPs@CDs as nanoprobes. The photoluminescence (PL) spectra of CDs and AgNPs@CDs were recorded, showing a peak at 420 nm for both under excitation at 340 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). Upon adding LST, a significant blue shift was observed, along with an increase in emission intensity, as LST concentrations ranged from 0.5 μM to 45 μM (Fig. 4). The shift and intensity increase were attributed to interactions between the hydroxyl and amine groups of LST and the carboxyl and hydroxyl groups on the nanoprobe surface, leading to nanoprobe aggregation [47]. Schematic illustration suggesting the probable mechanism behind the selective detection of LST by AgNPs@CDs has been demonstrated in Scheme 1
                        .

The developed sensor was evaluated for its ability to detect LST under optimized conditions. As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, the fluorescence intensity of AgNPs@CDs at 420 nm increased proportionally with LST concentrations between 0.5 μM and 45 μM. A linear relationship was observed between fluorescence intensity and LST concentrations in the range of 0.5 μM to 4.5 μM, with a regression equation of I/I0 = 0.0603 [LST] + 0.9036 and a correlation coefficient (R2) of 0.9904 (Fig. 6b). The detection limit (LOD) was calculated to be 180 nM based on a signal-to-noise ratio of 3 (S/N = 3). The developed sensor exhibited a competitive detection limit and dynamic range compared to other reported methods for LST detection (Table 1
                        ).
